posts.title: Planting seeds of change
posts.description: With each garden Volunteer Andrew and his community installs, another family has a source of nutrient rich vegetables a few steps from their kitchen door marking progress towards the final goal—a day when all children in Guatemala have the vitamins and nutrients they need to grow learn, play and be happy.

posts.title: Integration into a foreign culture: Reflections of a “Life Experienced Volunteer

posts.title: Initiating Cookstove Construction
posts.excerpt:
With students spectating and giggling
outside of the school kitchen, I started constructing the stove, sweating and
slightly nervous as this was the first stove I had constructed since my Pre-Service
Training.
posts.description:
Volunteer Justin helped make a series of fuel-efficient cookstoves to introduce them to community members.

Using these stoves, he held nutrition sessions and food-cooking demonstrations to help his Wildlife Club and a group of farmers understand why maintaining good nutrition is important and how these nutrients can be obtained. Amazing work!

posts.summary: Kolective: Empowering Young Seamstresses in Northern Benin
posts.title: Kolective: Empowering Young Seamstresses in Northern Benin
posts.excerpt: Kolective began as a grassroots project in the rural village of Cobly in northwest Benin. The project was started by Rural Community Health Volunteer Andrea Nasser as a way to empower adolescent seamstress apprentices by producing and selling handcrafted and unique fashion goods.
posts.description: Volunteer Andrea in Benin is teaching adolescent seamstress apprentices how to sell their handcrafted and unique fashion goods. So empowering!

posts.title: Instagram post by Peace Corps
posts.description:
The Peace Corps is all about bringing people and cultures together in the spirit of friendship and understanding. Starting up an international pen pal program is one way of making that happen, so that’s exactly what Volunteer Aryn did! 

“My kids were so excited, some of them even wrote two pages! 💕 Don’t worry, I will send a translation with each letter,” she says.

posts.title: Instagram post by Peace Corps
posts.description:
As 1 of 11 U.S. government agencies partnering to end hunger and reduce poverty, the Peace Corps is excited to continue supporting the Feed the Future initiative.

Since 2011, more than 4,000 Volunteers have worked on food security projects in 53 countries worldwide, directly benefiting over 150,000 people.

posts.title: Instagram post by Peace Corps
posts.description:
Bet you didn’t know you could do THIS in the Peace Corps!

As a Peace Corps Response Volunteer in Peru, Christopher Giordano supports a national program to develop a local artisanal fishing cooperative. He is also cataloging local fishing practices so that the art unique to his area can be recognized as cultural heritage of the entire country. So cool!

posts.title: Instagram post by Peace Corps
posts.description:
Volunteer Chris in Costa Rica recently attended a two-week course given by Instituto Nacional de Aprendizaje (INA), an organization that aims to promote efficiency, quality and consistency in local products.

In the training, Chris learned the process of making some of Costa Rica’s finest dairy products including queso crema (cream cheese), mascarpone, palmito, mozzarella, queso blanco, natilla casera (sour cream), dulce de leche (caramel), and helados (ice cream). Delicious!
